/-
Conjecture Cj.11 — Completeness of the A.1-A.4 axiom system: the four axioms
COMPLETELY characterize intelligent agents.

Reference: `~/Desktop/MIP/conjectures/index.md`
  * Cj.11 entry, line 21 ("Cj.11 | 完备性猜想（2026-05-18 范围扩展：A.4 升格后，
    完备性范围扩为 A.1-A.4 四公理）| 开放：可能不完备 | A.1-A.4");
  * meta-theory grouping, line ~871 ("完备性 / 元理论：Cj.11, Cj.7, Cj.13,
    Cj.18").
  * Directly related: R.108 (algorithmic incompleteness), formalized in
    `MIP/Results/R108_MipIncompleteness.lean`.

================================================================================
FAITHFUL NL CONJECTURE
================================================================================
The four axioms A.1-A.4 COMPLETELY characterize intelligent agents: there is no
true statement about agents (in the MIP language) that is independent of /
undecidable from A.1-A.4.  Equivalently, the deductive system generated by
A.1-A.4 is COMPLETE — every well-formed MIP-proposition is either provable or
refutable from the axioms (no independent extension is needed).

================================================================================
META-LEVEL CAVEAT
================================================================================
Completeness is a METATHEORETIC property of the axiom SYSTEM, not an object-level
proposition about a single agent.  It is a statement quantifying over ALL
well-formed propositions and the provability relation `⊢` — it lives in the
metatheory, not inside the object theory generated by A.1-A.4.  Hence it is
neither expressible nor decidable inside the object theory itself.  This is the
Gödelian situation, and it is reinforced by R.108: there is an algorithmically
undecidable (halting-coded) MIP-proposition, so the system is at least
algorithmically incomplete.

================================================================================
FORMALIZATION CHOICES
================================================================================
We model a deductive system abstractly:
  * `Sentence` : a type of well-formed MIP-propositions (Gödel-codeable);
  * `Provable  : Sentence → Prop` : the provability relation `⊢ φ` from A.1-A.4;
  * `Neg       : Sentence → Sentence` : object-level negation.

We capture two standard equivalent notions of completeness:

  (Syntactic / negation-completeness) `∀ φ, Provable φ ∨ Provable (Neg φ)` —
    every sentence is decided by the axioms.

  (Independence-freeness) there is NO sentence `φ` that is INDEPENDENT
    (neither `Provable φ` nor `Provable (Neg φ)`).

These are logically equivalent (each is the De Morgan dual of the other), which
we PROVE: `negationComplete ↔ noIndependentSentence`.  We also prove the
CONTRAPOSITIVE link to R.108-style undecidability: an independent sentence
witnesses incompleteness, and (under a soundness/decidability bridge hypothesis)
an algorithmically undecidable proposition family yields incompleteness.

What we do NOT and CANNOT do: decide `Cj11_Statement` itself.  Completeness is a
metatheoretic ∀-statement over the (axiom-defined, not here-constructed)
provability relation; it is out of scope of the object theory, and R.108
indicates the answer is "incomplete" in the algorithmic sense.

================================================================================
VERDICT: OPEN (expected NEGATIVE — incomplete, Gödelian).
================================================================================
  * `Cj11_Statement` (completeness of A.1-A.4) is OPEN as an object-theory
    question; metatheoretically the evidence (R.108) points to INCOMPLETE.  We
    RECORD the statement faithfully and prove the metatheoretic STRUCTURE around
    it (completeness ↔ no independent sentence; an undecidable sentence ⟹
    incomplete).
  * No object-theory proof is possible — see "BLOCKED AT".

This file is `sorry`-free and `axiom`-free.
-/
import Mathlib.Computability.Reduce
import Mathlib.Logic.Basic

namespace MIP

namespace Cj11

variable {Sentence : Type}

/-- **Negation-completeness (syntactic completeness).**

The deductive system `Provable` (generated by A.1-A.4), with object-level
negation `Neg`, is negation-complete iff every sentence is decided: provable or
its negation is provable. -/
def negationComplete (Provable : Sentence → Prop) (Neg : Sentence → Sentence) :
    Prop :=
  ∀ φ : Sentence, Provable φ ∨ Provable (Neg φ)

/-- **A sentence is INDEPENDENT** of the system iff neither it nor its negation
is provable. -/
def Independent (Provable : Sentence → Prop) (Neg : Sentence → Sentence)
    (φ : Sentence) : Prop :=
  ¬ Provable φ ∧ ¬ Provable (Neg φ)

/-- **No independent sentence** exists. -/
def noIndependentSentence (Provable : Sentence → Prop)
    (Neg : Sentence → Sentence) : Prop :=
  ¬ ∃ φ : Sentence, Independent Provable Neg φ

/-- **Faithful statement of Cj.11 (completeness of A.1-A.4).**

The MIP axiom system `Provable` (over the sentence type with negation `Neg`) is
COMPLETE: it is negation-complete.  This `def` RECORDS the metatheoretic
proposition (it compiles, no `sorry`); the file does NOT assert it is provable —
it is OPEN, and the R.108 evidence points to its NEGATION (see BLOCKED AT). -/
def Cj11_Statement (Provable : Sentence → Prop) (Neg : Sentence → Sentence) :
    Prop :=
  negationComplete Provable Neg

/-- **Completeness ⟺ no independent sentence (PROVED).**

The two standard formulations of completeness coincide: the system decides every
sentence iff there is no sentence independent of it.  Pure logical (De Morgan)
equivalence, valid classically. -/
theorem complete_iff_noIndependent
    (Provable : Sentence → Prop) (Neg : Sentence → Sentence) :
    negationComplete Provable Neg ↔ noIndependentSentence Provable Neg := by
  unfold negationComplete noIndependentSentence Independent
  constructor
  · -- complete ⟹ no independent sentence
    intro hcomp ⟨φ, hnp, hnnp⟩
    rcases hcomp φ with h | h
    · exact hnp h
    · exact hnnp h
  · -- no independent sentence ⟹ complete (uses classical `em`)
    intro hno φ
    by_contra hcon
    -- hcon : ¬(Provable φ ∨ Provable (Neg φ)); split via `not_or`.
    exact hno ⟨φ, (not_or.mp hcon).1, (not_or.mp hcon).2⟩

/-- **An independent sentence refutes completeness (PROVED).**

If some sentence `φ` is independent of the system, the system is NOT complete.
This is the bridge from "∃ undecidable proposition" (R.108-style) to
"incomplete". -/
theorem incomplete_of_independent
    (Provable : Sentence → Prop) (Neg : Sentence → Sentence)
    {φ : Sentence} (hφ : Independent Provable Neg φ) :
    ¬ negationComplete Provable Neg := by
  rw [complete_iff_noIndependent]
  -- goal: ¬ noIndependentSentence = ¬¬∃ φ, Independent …
  unfold noIndependentSentence
  exact not_not.mpr ⟨φ, hφ⟩

/-! ### Link to R.108 (algorithmic incompleteness)

R.108 (`MIP/Results/R108_MipIncompleteness.lean`) shows there is an
algorithmically UNDECIDABLE MIP-proposition family `phiMIP : ℕ → Prop` (its
truth value tracks the halting predicate).  We record the bridge: under a
"soundness + completeness ⟹ decidability" hypothesis (i.e. if a complete sound
system's provable sentences were the true ones, the truth predicate would be
decidable by enumerating proofs), algorithmic undecidability forces
incompleteness.  We state the contrapositive kernel abstractly, without assuming
the bridge inside the object theory. -/

/-- **Algorithmic-incompleteness bridge (PROVED, hypothesis-bundled).**

Model the truth/decision predicate of the system as `decide : ℕ → Prop` on coded
sentences.  Suppose (bridge `hbridge`) that IF the system were complete then its
decision predicate would be algorithmically decidable — the standard
"complete + axiomatizable ⟹ decidable" metatheorem (provability is r.e.; a
complete system makes truth = provability, hence decidable by dovetailing).
Then R.108's `¬ ComputablePred decide` forces the system to be INCOMPLETE.

This faithfully connects Cj.11 to R.108: the system is at least algorithmically
incomplete.  The bridge is carried as an explicit hypothesis (it is a
metatheorem about the object system, not derivable inside it). -/
theorem incomplete_of_undecidable_via_bridge
    (decide : ℕ → Prop)
    (CompleteFlag : Prop)
    (hbridge : CompleteFlag → ComputablePred decide)
    (hundec : ¬ ComputablePred decide) :
    ¬ CompleteFlag :=
  fun hc => hundec (hbridge hc)

/-! ### Sanity / faithfulness checks -/

/-- Sanity: a system that is INCONSISTENT in the strong sense of proving every
sentence (`∀ φ, Provable φ`) is vacuously negation-complete — illustrating that
negation-completeness alone does not capture consistency, exactly why the
genuine Cj.11 question (consistent AND complete) is subtle. -/
example (Provable : Sentence → Prop) (Neg : Sentence → Sentence)
    (htrivial : ∀ φ, Provable φ) :
    negationComplete Provable Neg :=
  fun φ => Or.inl (htrivial φ)

/-- Sanity: if there is a designated independent sentence, completeness fails —
the precise mechanism by which an R.108-style undecidable proposition would
refute Cj.11. -/
example (Provable : Sentence → Prop) (Neg : Sentence → Sentence)
    (φ : Sentence) (h : Independent Provable Neg φ) :
    ¬ Cj11_Statement Provable Neg :=
  incomplete_of_independent Provable Neg h

/-! ### BLOCKED AT — verdict OPEN (metatheoretic; expected NEGATIVE)

The metatheoretic STRUCTURE around Cj.11 is proven above (completeness ⟺ no
independent sentence; an independent / undecidable proposition ⟹ incomplete; the
R.108 bridge).  The conjecture `Cj11_Statement` ITSELF is OPEN as an object-level
question and OUT OF SCOPE of the object theory.

MISSING / WHY OUT OF SCOPE (not expressible or provable inside A.1-A.4):

  1. METATHEORETIC, NOT OBJECT-LEVEL.  "A.1-A.4 are complete" quantifies over ALL
     well-formed propositions AND the provability relation `⊢`.  The object
     theory of A.1-A.4 (`MIP.Axioms`: `N`, `Φ₀`, `K`, `ℛ`, …) has no internal
     predicate `Provable` and no Gödel-coding of its own sentences; the
     statement cannot even be FORMULATED inside the object theory.  It can only
     be posed in a metatheory (as we do here, abstractly).

  2. GÖDELIAN INCOMPLETENESS (R.108).  R.108
     (`R108_MipIncompleteness.lean`) exhibits an algorithmically UNDECIDABLE
     MIP-proposition family (truth value = halting predicate).  Via
     `incomplete_of_undecidable_via_bridge`, this is direct evidence that the
     system is INCOMPLETE in the algorithmic sense — so the EXPECTED answer to
     Cj.11 is NEGATIVE.  But turning algorithmic incompleteness into FULL
     (logical) negation-incompleteness needs the "complete + r.e.-axiomatizable
     ⟹ decidable" bridge, which is itself a metatheorem requiring a fixed
     formal language and proof system for MIP — neither of which A.1-A.4
     supply.

  3. NO FIXED FORMAL LANGUAGE / PROOF CALCULUS FOR MIP.  To even ask whether the
     axioms are complete one must fix (i) the language of MIP-sentences, (ii) a
     proof calculus.  The current project specifies axioms semantically (as Lean
     `axiom` declarations over opaque symbols), not as a self-contained formal
     system with its own syntax — so "completeness of A.1-A.4" has no
     object-theoretic referent to decide.

Therefore the honest verdict is OPEN (expected NEGATIVE / incomplete): a faithful
metatheoretic statement plus the surrounding structure and the R.108 link is the
deliverable; no object-theory proof or refutation is possible. -/

end Cj11

end MIP
